	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=14&mid=101233827334868>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=14&mid=101233827334868>RE: DoT questions</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=14&mid=101233827334868#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jan 29th 5:06 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=49677><span id=Guru>alaaraaf the Puissant</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>179 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Hey.<br><br>I suspect that what you were told was a little, erm, inaccurate.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are two things, that may explain what you have heard:<br><br><LI><b>On a merry-go-round:</b><br>You may, or may not be aware, that EverQuest doesn't update constantly.  You might have noticed, that if you are running and stop, (even if you wait a second, to be sure you have come to a complete stop,) you will fail when casting a spell.  This is because although you have stopped, your position hasn't updated and the server believes you were moving, when you started to cast.  And thus you are interrupted.<br>If you turn, you force your PC to update the server.  Thus it knows you have stopped running and the spell is not interrupted.  Thus, all you have to do, is stop and tap the left, or right cursor and then cast.<br><span style='color: green;'><b>I read this on the official EverQuest website.  (I think, on the developer's forum.)  This is not my pet theory, or a guess, it is Verant's official response.  (The suggestion to turn, after stopping was Verant's.)  If you don't believe me, go check it out yourself.  If you don't like it, tough!</b></span style='color: green;'><br><i>(Forgive the tone of the above remark.  But, some fool gave one of my posts a lousy rating, stating what I had written was wrong, while forwarding their own suggestion as fact!  (My comment was speculation, but I had not tried to present it as anything else!  *Shrug*)</i><br><br><LI><b>&quot;Let's go fly a kite, up where the air is bright...&quot;</b><br>Have you ever watched druids kiting mobs?  Have you ever felt the green touch of, (no, not of <span style='color: green;'>Pusbag</span style='color: green;'>,) envy, as you watch them kill four mobs at a time?  <br>Quite some way back, the way DoTs worked was, well, from a certain point of view, nerfed.  The change that was made, was that if a mob was buy trying to get to you, to rip your face open, it wouldn't take full damage from a DoT.  <i>(It would in fact take around half damage.)</i>  However, if the mob was Feared and running away, it would still take full damage, so it makes little difference to a necromancer.<br>I'm given to believe that this change was made, primarily, to balance out druids, who it was felt were too powerful.<br><i>(I'm not absolutely certain how this works with Root.  I have been told that a Rooted mob also takes less damage.  This has not been my experience, <b>but</b> I usually Root and then Fear.  (So that if Root breaks, the mob is running away and not trying to release my entrails!)  Obviously, this approach requires the right circumstances to work!)</i><br><br>Anyhow, I hope this helps.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br></p>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></td></tr>
